00:11:20,960 --> 00:11:22,600
And basically what that means is that if

269
00:11:22,600 --> 00:11:24,760
I want to close that spread at expiration,

270
00:11:25,340 --> 00:11:27,640
I could sell the $135 call for $20,

271
00:11:28,180 --> 00:11:32,260
collecting $2,000 in premium, and I would

272
00:11:32,260 --> 00:11:35,140
have to buy back the short $150 call

273
00:11:35,140 --> 00:11:39,600
for $5, therefore paying out $500 in premium,

274
00:11:40,080 --> 00:11:42,020
and that would leave me with a net

275
00:11:42,020 --> 00:11:45,880
premium collection of $1,500 at expiration.

276
00:11:46,520 --> 00:11:49,020
So this is the expiration payoff graph, which

277
00:11:49,020 --> 00:11:51,620
only really matters at expiration, but how did

278
00:11:51,620 --> 00:11:54,240
this strategy actually perform as the stock price

279
00:11:54,240 --> 00:11:55,500
changed over time?

280
00:11:55,500 --> 00:11:56,760
Let's take a look.

281
00:11:57,220 --> 00:11:58,920
On the top portion of this graph, we

282
00:11:58,920 --> 00:12:01,220
have the changes in the stock price relative

283
00:12:01,220 --> 00:12:03,220
to the strike prices of this call spread,

284
00:12:03,480 --> 00:12:05,300
and on the bottom portion of the graph,

285
00:12:05,440 --> 00:12:07,440
we're looking at the actual changes in the

286
00:12:07,440 --> 00:12:10,000
spread's value as the stock price changed.

287
00:12:10,640 --> 00:12:12,340
In the first few days of the trade,

288
00:12:12,640 --> 00:12:15,300
the stock price drifted lower, which caused the

289
00:12:15,300 --> 00:12:16,540
call spread to lose value.

290
00:12:17,160 --> 00:12:18,960
If the spread price declines from the price

291
00:12:18,960 --> 00:12:21,240
you pay for it, you'll have an unrealized

292
00:12:21,240 --> 00:12:21,580
loss.

293
00:12:22,080 --> 00:12:24,160
Fortunately, we can see that the stock price

294
00:12:24,160 --> 00:12:27,040
rocketed higher in the subsequent weeks, leading to

295
00:12:27,040 --> 00:12:29,060
an increase in the call spread's value.

296
00:12:29,640 --> 00:12:31,460
You'll notice that there was a moment where

297
00:12:31,460 --> 00:12:33,660
the stock price was above the entire call

298
00:12:33,660 --> 00:12:36,560
spread, but why wasn't the spread's price $15?

299
00:12:37,380 --> 00:12:39,240
Because I know I said that the maximum

300
00:12:39,240 --> 00:12:41,880
value of this spread at expiration would be

301
00:12:41,880 --> 00:12:45,480
$15 if the stock price was above $150.

302
00:12:46,220 --> 00:12:48,100
Well, we will talk about that later in

303
00:12:48,100 --> 00:12:51,400
the section titled Vertical Spread Profitability vs.

304
00:12:51,660 --> 00:12:52,620
Time to Expiration.

305
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:55,460
At around 4 days to expiration, the spread's

306
00:12:55,460 --> 00:12:58,040
price was very close to its maximum value

307
00:12:58,040 --> 00:12:58,760
of $15.

308
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:01,500
It's worth mentioning here that you can close

309
00:13:01,500 --> 00:13:04,080
a vertical spread whenever you want to, you

310
00:13:04,080 --> 00:13:06,020
don't have to hold until expiration.

311
00:13:06,760 --> 00:13:09,060
If the maximum potential value of the spread

312
00:13:09,060 --> 00:13:11,920
is $15, and the spread's price gets close

313
00:13:11,920 --> 00:13:14,560
to $15, then it makes sense to close

314
00:13:14,560 --> 00:13:16,840
the trade because you have very little left

315
00:13:16,840 --> 00:13:18,920
to gain from holding it, but you have

316
00:13:18,920 --> 00:13:19,800
everything to lose.

317
00:13:20,020 --> 00:13:21,320
At the very end of the trade, we

318
00:13:21,320 --> 00:13:23,080
can see that the stock price did dip

319
00:13:23,080 --> 00:13:25,920
lower and the call spread lost substantial value,

320
00:13:26,200 --> 00:13:28,040
and that's exactly why a spread should be

321
00:13:28,040 --> 00:13:31,160
closed when it approaches the maximum potential value.

322
00:13:31,400 --> 00:13:32,800
It's really not worth holding.

323
00:13:33,100 --> 00:13:35,120
At the time of expiration, the stock price

324
00:13:35,120 --> 00:13:38,420
was at $148.06, leaving the trade with

325
00:13:38,420 --> 00:13:40,260
a profit of $530.

326
00:13:40,880 --> 00:13:42,660
But where does this profit come from?

327
00:13:43,080 --> 00:13:46,460
If the stock price is at $148.06

328
00:13:46,460 --> 00:13:50,340
at expiration, the 135 call will have intrinsic

329
00:13:50,340 --> 00:13:54,480
value of $13.06, while the 150 call

330
00:13:54,480 --> 00:13:57,660
will have no intrinsic value and expire worthless.

331
00:13:58,640 --> 00:14:00,660
Therefore, the value of the spread at expiration

332
00:14:00,660 --> 00:14:03,860
is limited to the intrinsic value of the

333
00:14:03,860 --> 00:14:08,200
135 call, which is $13.06, meaning that

334
00:14:08,200 --> 00:14:11,440
in actual dollar terms, the spread's value would

335
00:14:11,440 --> 00:14:12,960
be $1306.

336
00:14:13,520 --> 00:14:16,880
And if I buy a spread for $776

337
00:14:16,880 --> 00:14:21,260
and it expires with a value of $1306,

338
00:14:21,860 --> 00:14:24,440
my profit is $530.

339
00:14:24,980 --> 00:14:26,980
So what we've learned with this example is

340
00:14:26,980 --> 00:14:29,160
that when you buy a call spread, or

341
00:14:29,160 --> 00:14:32,080
you trade a bull call spread, you want

342
00:14:32,080 --> 00:14:34,680
the stock price to increase, and ideally you

343
00:14:34,680 --> 00:14:37,320
want the stock price to be above the

344
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:39,820
upper strike price of the bull call spread

345
00:14:39,820 --> 00:14:42,440
at the time of expiration, as that is

346
00:14:42,440 --> 00:14:44,440
a scenario that will result in the spread

347
00:14:44,440 --> 00:14:47,980
having its maximum potential value, which we also

348
00:14:47,980 --> 00:14:50,820
learned is the distance between the strike prices.

349
00:14:51,280 --> 00:14:53,180
So if I have a $20 wide vertical

350
00:14:53,180 --> 00:14:55,000
spread, the most it can be worth is

351
00:14:55,000 --> 00:14:55,320
$20.

352
00:14:56,100 --> 00:14:58,760
If I have a $100 wide vertical spread,

353
00:14:59,400 --> 00:15:01,000
the most that spread can be worth at

354
00:15:01,000 --> 00:15:02,620
expiration is $100.

355
00:15:03,240 --> 00:15:04,580
So keep that in mind.

356
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:06,780
We also saw that as the stock price

357
00:15:06,780 --> 00:15:09,200
goes up and down, so does the value

358
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:10,320
of the call spread.

359
00:15:10,800 --> 00:15:13,300
And this is important to understand because when

360
00:15:13,300 --> 00:15:15,900
you enter any option position, it's not a

361
00:15:15,900 --> 00:15:18,500
binary event where you only get the profit

362
00:15:18,500 --> 00:15:19,940
or loss at the time of expiration.

363
00:15:20,400 --> 00:15:23,120
The option prices, or the option spread in

364
00:15:23,120 --> 00:15:25,760
this example, will change every minute of the

365
00:15:25,760 --> 00:15:28,040
day as the stock price is changing, and

366
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:29,840
you can get out of that spread or

367
00:15:29,840 --> 00:15:31,840
option position whenever you want to.

368
00:15:32,220 --> 00:15:34,180
So just because it has an expiration date,

369
00:15:34,440 --> 00:15:36,000
it doesn't mean you have to hold until

370
00:15:36,000 --> 00:15:36,920
the expiration date.

371
00:15:37,180 --> 00:15:38,920
So to close the call spread in this

372
00:15:38,920 --> 00:15:42,120
example, since I bought the $135 call as

373
00:15:42,120 --> 00:15:44,580
an opening trade, and I shorted the $150

374
00:15:44,580 --> 00:15:47,240
call when I opened the trade, to close

375
00:15:47,240 --> 00:15:49,600
this call spread, I just have to sell

376
00:15:49,600 --> 00:15:52,320
the $135 call that I own and buy

377
00:15:52,320 --> 00:15:54,360
back the $150 call that I am short.

378
00:15:54,840 --> 00:15:56,620
And you can do this in one transaction

379
00:15:56,620 --> 00:16:00,040
at one spread price, and effectively that will

380
00:16:00,040 --> 00:16:02,760
realize whatever profit or loss you have on

381
00:16:02,760 --> 00:16:04,300
that spread at that moment.

382
00:16:04,700 --> 00:16:06,340
So you never have to hold a spread

383
00:16:06,340 --> 00:16:07,140
until expiration.

384
00:16:07,580 --> 00:16:09,100
You can close it whenever you want.

385
00:16:09,440 --> 00:16:11,000
So I could buy a call spread and

386
00:16:11,000 --> 00:16:12,900
sell it five seconds later if I wanted

387
00:16:12,900 --> 00:16:13,160
to.

388
00:16:13,560 --> 00:16:15,400
I can get out whenever I want to.

389
00:16:15,460 --> 00:16:16,920
All right, let's move on to the second

390
00:16:16,920 --> 00:16:19,840
bullish vertical spread, which is called the bull

391
00:16:19,840 --> 00:16:20,680
put spread.

392
00:16:21,020 --> 00:16:23,360
As the name suggests, a bull put spread

393
00:16:23,360 --> 00:16:27,000
is a bullish vertical spread constructed with put

394
00:16:27,000 --> 00:16:29,580
options as opposed to call options, which we

395
00:16:29,580 --> 00:16:30,400
just discussed.

396
00:16:30,860 --> 00:16:33,540
To set up a bull put spread, a

397
00:16:33,540 --> 00:16:35,720
trader will short a put option at one

398
00:16:35,720 --> 00:16:38,940
strike price and purchase another put option at

399
00:16:38,940 --> 00:16:40,420
a lower strike price.

400
00:16:40,900 --> 00:16:43,120
Now this is sometimes just referred to as

401
00:16:43,120 --> 00:16:45,880
selling or shorting a put spread, but it

402
00:16:45,880 --> 00:16:48,400
is also referred to as a put credit

403
00:16:48,400 --> 00:16:50,900
spread because when you enter the trade, you

404
00:16:50,900 --> 00:16:53,740
will collect a net credit, meaning the option

405
00:16:53,740 --> 00:16:55,540
that you sell is more expensive than the

406
00:16:55,540 --> 00:16:58,280
option you purchase, and therefore you will collect

407
00:16:58,280 --> 00:16:59,940
premium when you enter the trade.

408
00:17:00,340 --> 00:17:01,860
And that's why it's called a credit spread.

409
00:17:02,080 --> 00:17:04,180
The goal when trading a bull put spread

410
00:17:04,180 --> 00:17:07,040
is to see the stock price increase, but

411
00:17:07,040 --> 00:17:09,060
at the very least, the trade can make

412
00:17:09,060 --> 00:17:11,480
money so long as the stock price remains

413
00:17:11,480 --> 00:17:14,680
above the short put strike price as time

414
00:17:14,680 --> 00:17:15,240
passes.

415
00:17:15,740 --> 00:17:17,520
So if the stock price is here and

416
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:19,660
you sell this put spread here, you can

417
00:17:19,660 --> 00:17:21,460
make money so long as the stock price

418
00:17:21,460 --> 00:17:23,119
remains above this put spread.

419
00:17:23,640 --> 00:17:25,940
And that means it is a high probability

420
00:17:25,940 --> 00:17:29,100
trading strategy, meaning that you have a greater

421
00:17:29,100 --> 00:17:32,320
than 50% chance, in theory, of making

422
00:17:32,320 --> 00:17:33,460
money on that trade.

423
00:17:33,620 --> 00:17:35,400
So just like we did before, let's go

424
00:17:35,400 --> 00:17:37,680
ahead and look at a real historical example.

425
00:17:38,360 --> 00:17:40,600
In this example, the stock price is at

426
00:17:40,600 --> 00:17:44,900
$146.92 at the time of entering the

427
00:17:44,900 --> 00:17:45,160
trade.

428
00:17:45,760 --> 00:17:48,100
To construct this bull put spread, we will

429
00:17:48,100 --> 00:17:51,940
short the $145 put and collect $6.60

430
00:17:51,940 --> 00:17:56,800
and simultaneously purchase the $135 put for $3

431
00:17:56,800 --> 00:18:00,840
.07. Both options are in the 46-day

432
00:18:00,840 --> 00:18:01,840
expiration cycle.

433
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:04,240
The entry price for this spread is $3

434
00:18:04,240 --> 00:18:08,180
.53 that is received since I shorted the

435
00:18:08,180 --> 00:18:12,400
$145 put and collected $6.60 and paid

436
00:18:12,400 --> 00:18:16,320
$3.07 to buy the $135 put.

437
00:18:16,760 --> 00:18:19,260
So a net premium is collected at entry.

438
00:18:19,660 --> 00:18:23,380
The breakeven price for this particular position is

439
00:18:23,380 --> 00:18:26,640
$141.47. And that means if the stock

440
00:18:26,640 --> 00:18:29,900
price is at $141.47 at the time

441
00:18:29,900 --> 00:18:32,320
of expiration, then this put spread will not

442
00:18:32,320 --> 00:18:33,800
make or lose any money.

443
00:18:34,080 --> 00:18:36,080
So remember earlier I said that the maximum

444
00:18:36,080 --> 00:18:38,600
value of a vertical spread is the distance

445
00:18:38,600 --> 00:18:40,860
between the strike prices, and in this case,

446
00:18:41,040 --> 00:18:43,620
since the put strikes are $10 apart, the

447
00:18:43,620 --> 00:18:45,840
maximum value of this put spread at expiration

448
00:18:45,840 --> 00:18:46,960
is $10.

449
00:18:47,500 --> 00:18:50,080
So let's look at the expiration payoff diagram

450
00:18:50,080 --> 00:18:53,240
for this particular bull put spread position.

451
00:18:53,760 --> 00:18:55,540
So as we can see here, the best

452
00:18:55,540 --> 00:18:57,320
case scenario is that the stock price is

453
00:18:57,320 --> 00:18:59,660
above the entire put spread at expiration.

454
00:19:00,360 --> 00:19:03,380
If the stock price is above $145 at

455
00:19:03,380 --> 00:19:07,600
expiration, the $145 put and the $135 put

456
00:19:07,600 --> 00:19:10,560
will have no intrinsic value and therefore will

457
00:19:10,560 --> 00:19:13,420
expire worthless, leaving the spread with a value

458
00:19:13,420 --> 00:19:13,880
of $0.

459
00:19:14,420 --> 00:19:17,900
If I collect $353 for this spread at

460
00:19:17,900 --> 00:19:20,720
entry and the spread's price falls to $0,

461
00:19:20,720 --> 00:19:23,440
I will effectively make 100% of the

462
00:19:23,440 --> 00:19:25,940
profit potential, or $353.

463
00:19:26,800 --> 00:19:28,720
And so when you short a put spread

464
00:19:28,720 --> 00:19:30,580
like this, you want all of the options

465
00:19:30,580 --> 00:19:33,340
to expire worthless, which will happen if the

466
00:19:33,340 --> 00:19:36,560
stock price increases and is above both put

467
00:19:36,560 --> 00:19:39,200
spread's strike prices at the time of expiration.

468
00:19:39,800 --> 00:19:42,420
The expiration breakeven price of this position is

469
00:19:42,420 --> 00:19:45,720
$141.47, which means if the stock price

470
00:19:45,720 --> 00:19:51,120
is at $141.47 at expiration, the $145

471
00:19:51,120 --> 00:19:53,600
put will be worth its intrinsic value of

472
00:19:53,600 --> 00:19:57,080
$3.53, and the $135 put will be

473
00:19:57,080 --> 00:19:57,520
worthless.

474
00:19:58,020 --> 00:20:00,580
And lastly, the maximum loss potential of this

475
00:20:00,580 --> 00:20:04,360
position is $647, which will occur if the

476
00:20:04,360 --> 00:20:06,920
stock price is below both put spread's strike

477
00:20:06,920 --> 00:20:08,040
prices at expiration.

478
00:20:08,460 --> 00:20:11,920
If the stock price is below $135 at

479
00:20:11,920 --> 00:20:14,120
expiration, then the put spread will be worth

480
00:20:14,120 --> 00:20:17,880
its maximum value of $10, which again is

481
00:20:17,880 --> 00:20:19,960
the distance between the two strike prices.

482
00:20:20,600 --> 00:20:22,540
So if I shorted this spread initially and

483
00:20:22,540 --> 00:20:27,760
collected $353 in premium and the value increased

484
00:20:27,760 --> 00:20:30,300
to $1,000, which is its maximum value,

485
00:20:30,800 --> 00:20:33,300
then I will lose $647.

486
00:20:34,040 --> 00:20:35,400
So let's go ahead and take a look

487
00:20:35,400 --> 00:20:37,400
and see exactly what happened to this bull

488
00:20:37,400 --> 00:20:39,860
put spread in real life as the stock

489
00:20:39,860 --> 00:20:42,480
price was changing up and down through the

490
00:20:42,480 --> 00:20:43,320
trade's duration.

491
00:20:43,780 --> 00:20:45,420
So again, the top portion of this graph

492
00:20:45,420 --> 00:20:47,560
features the changes in the stock price relative

493
00:20:47,560 --> 00:20:49,260
to the spread's strike prices.

494
00:20:49,780 --> 00:20:51,300
As we can see early on in the

495
00:20:51,300 --> 00:20:53,940
trade, the share price was falling, which actually

496
00:20:53,940 --> 00:20:56,460
caused an increase in the put spread's value.

497
00:20:57,120 --> 00:20:58,620
And since the bull put spread is a

498
00:20:58,620 --> 00:21:00,660
bullish strategy, it will lose money when the

499
00:21:00,660 --> 00:21:02,800
stock price falls, and it will make money

500
00:21:02,800 --> 00:21:04,340
when the stock price rises.

501
00:21:05,160 --> 00:21:08,160
Fortunately, the shares regained traction and headed higher

502
00:21:08,160 --> 00:21:09,860
throughout the remainder of the trade.

503
00:21:10,540 --> 00:21:12,300
And we can see that the further the

504
00:21:12,300 --> 00:21:15,240
stock price increased, and as time passed, the

505
00:21:15,240 --> 00:21:16,660
spread's value collapsed.

506
00:21:17,040 --> 00:21:19,520
At around 17 days to expiration, the spread's

507
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:22,320
value was already very close to $0, which

508
00:21:22,320 --> 00:21:25,200
means the trade essentially already had the maximum

509
00:21:25,200 --> 00:21:26,060
profit potential.

510
00:21:26,540 --> 00:21:28,480
And at that moment, a wise trader would

511
00:21:28,480 --> 00:21:30,780
close the put spread to secure the near

512
00:21:30,780 --> 00:21:31,640
-maximum profit.

513
00:21:32,200 --> 00:21:34,640
Closing the put spread would entail buying back

514
00:21:34,640 --> 00:21:38,020
the short $145 put and selling the long

515
00:21:38,020 --> 00:21:38,980
$135 put.

516
00:21:39,420 --> 00:21:41,120
The P&L on the trade would therefore

517
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:44,840
be the difference between the $353 in premium

518
00:21:44,840 --> 00:21:47,320
collected at the time of entering the trade

519
00:21:47,320 --> 00:21:49,900
and whatever they paid to close the spread.

520
00:21:50,480 --> 00:21:52,900
So if they paid $20 to close the

521
00:21:52,900 --> 00:21:55,000
spread, the profit on the trade would be

522
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:56,660
$333.

523
00:21:57,520 --> 00:21:59,420
But as we can see, the spread continued

524
00:21:59,420 --> 00:22:02,120
losing value and ended up with the maximum

525
00:22:02,120 --> 00:22:03,320
profit at expiration.

526
00:22:04,000 --> 00:22:08,060
Because with the stock price at $157.02

527
00:22:08,060 --> 00:22:12,200
at expiration, the $145 put and the $135

528
00:22:12,200 --> 00:22:15,780
put had no intrinsic value, and therefore the

529
00:22:15,780 --> 00:22:17,140
spread's value was $0.

530
00:22:17,680 --> 00:22:19,800
So thus far we've covered both of the

531
00:22:19,800 --> 00:22:22,560
bullish vertical spread trading strategies, which are the

532
00:22:22,560 --> 00:22:24,460
bull call spread, which is buying a call

533
00:22:24,460 --> 00:22:27,100
spread, and the bull put spread, which is

534
00:22:27,100 --> 00:22:28,680
shorting a put spread.

535
00:22:29,260 --> 00:22:30,800
So one of those is referred to as

536
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:33,000
a debit spread, meaning you pay to enter

537
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:34,780
it, which is buying the call spread.

538
00:22:35,180 --> 00:22:36,820
And one of those is referred to as

539
00:22:36,820 --> 00:22:39,340
a credit spread, which means you collect premium

540
00:22:39,340 --> 00:22:41,540
when you enter the trade, and that is

541
00:22:41,540 --> 00:22:44,100
when you sell or short the put spread.

542
00:22:44,420 --> 00:22:46,480
So you may be wondering, when would you

543
00:22:46,480 --> 00:22:48,340
use the bull call spread and when would

544
00:22:48,340 --> 00:22:49,700
you use the bull put spread?

545
00:22:49,700 --> 00:22:51,900
And we'll talk about that later in the

546
00:22:51,900 --> 00:22:54,740
section titled, How to Select the Right Strategy.

547
00:22:55,300 --> 00:22:56,580
But for now we need to move on

548
00:22:56,580 --> 00:22:59,160
to the bearish vertical spread trades, which are

549
00:22:59,160 --> 00:23:01,300
the bear call spread and the bear put

550
00:23:01,300 --> 00:23:01,500
spread.

551
00:23:01,800 --> 00:23:02,860
So let's get started.

552
00:23:03,120 --> 00:23:04,980
So the first of these bearish vertical spread

553
00:23:04,980 --> 00:23:06,880
trades that we will cover is called the

554
00:23:06,880 --> 00:23:09,640
bear call spread, which is basically when you

555
00:23:09,640 --> 00:23:12,320
sell a call spread or short a call

556
00:23:12,320 --> 00:23:12,560
spread.

557
00:23:13,080 --> 00:23:15,440
So the bear call spread is sometimes referred

558
00:23:15,440 --> 00:23:17,900
to as simply selling a call spread, a

559
00:23:17,900 --> 00:23:20,860
call credit spread, and that's it.

560
00:23:21,040 --> 00:23:22,940
The next strategy we will cover is called

561
00:23:22,940 --> 00:23:25,480
the bear call spread, which is referred to

562
00:23:25,480 --> 00:23:28,220
sometimes as selling a call spread or a

563
00:23:28,220 --> 00:23:29,460
call credit spread.

564
00:23:29,820 --> 00:23:32,760
And a bear call spread is constructed by

565
00:23:32,760 --> 00:23:35,160
shorting a call option at one strike price

566
00:23:35,160 --> 00:23:38,140
and purchasing another call option at a higher

567
00:23:38,140 --> 00:23:39,040
strike price.

568
00:23:39,220 --> 00:23:41,500
So it's basically the bull call spread from

569
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:44,060
earlier, except you do the opposite, and instead

570
00:23:44,060 --> 00:23:46,820
of buying the call spread, you actually short

571
00:23:46,820 --> 00:23:49,180
or sell the call spread as your opening

572
00:23:49,180 --> 00:23:49,540
trade.

573
00:23:49,880 --> 00:23:51,400
And a bear call spread will make money

574
00:23:51,400 --> 00:23:53,740
as long as the stock price remains below

575
00:23:53,740 --> 00:23:55,520
the call spread's strike prices.

576
00:23:55,920 --> 00:23:57,160
So if you sell this call spread and

577
00:23:57,160 --> 00:23:58,920
the stock price is here, it doesn't matter

578
00:23:58,920 --> 00:24:00,280
if the stock price goes up a little

579
00:24:00,280 --> 00:24:02,220
bit, as long as the stock price is

580
00:24:02,220 --> 00:24:05,520
below the vertical spread's strike prices, the trade

581
00:24:05,520 --> 00:24:07,100
will make money as time passes.

582
00:24:07,260 --> 00:24:08,560
So let's look at an example.

583
00:24:09,040 --> 00:24:11,000
In this example, the stock price is at

584
00:24:11,000 --> 00:24:15,260
$141.46 at the time of entry, and

585
00:24:15,260 --> 00:24:17,560
to construct this spread, I will short the

586
00:24:17,560 --> 00:24:21,300
$142 call for $1.93 and buy the

587
00:24:21,300 --> 00:24:25,140
$145 call for $0.87. Both options are

588
00:24:25,140 --> 00:24:27,020
in the 32-day expiration cycle.

589
00:24:27,720 --> 00:24:29,680
So the entry price for this spread is

590
00:24:29,680 --> 00:24:33,800
$1.06 that is received, since the call

591
00:24:33,800 --> 00:24:37,020
that I shorted, the $142 call, is more

592
00:24:37,020 --> 00:24:39,260
expensive than the call that I purchased, and

593
00:24:39,260 --> 00:24:42,060
this results in a net premium collection at

594
00:24:42,060 --> 00:24:43,540
the time of entering the trade.

595
00:24:43,840 --> 00:24:46,400
So let's look at the expiration payoff graph

596
00:24:46,400 --> 00:24:47,440
for this position.

597
00:24:47,840 --> 00:24:49,900
As we can see, the best case scenario

598
00:24:49,900 --> 00:24:52,660
is that the stock price is below $142

599
00:24:52,660 --> 00:24:54,980
at expiration, as that would lead to the

600
00:24:54,980 --> 00:24:59,520
$142 and $145 calls expiring worthless, which means

601
00:24:59,520 --> 00:25:01,280
the call spread's value is $0.

602
00:25:01,800 --> 00:25:04,520
If I short the call spread for $106

603
00:25:04,520 --> 00:25:07,540
and it expires worthless, I'll make the full

604
00:25:07,540 --> 00:25:09,260
profit of $106.

605
00:25:10,040 --> 00:25:13,620
The breakeven price is $143.06, which means

606
00:25:13,620 --> 00:25:16,540
if the stock price is right at $143

607
00:25:16,540 --> 00:25:20,980
.06 at expiration, the $142 call will have

608
00:25:20,980 --> 00:25:25,260
intrinsic value of $1.06, and the $145

609
00:25:25,260 --> 00:25:28,020
call will expire worthless, leaving the spread with

610
00:25:28,020 --> 00:25:31,780
a value of $1.06. No profit, no

611
00:25:31,780 --> 00:25:32,160
loss.

612
00:25:32,820 --> 00:25:34,400
Now if the stock price is at or

613
00:25:34,400 --> 00:25:38,060
above the upper strike of $145, the call

614
00:25:38,060 --> 00:25:40,420
spread will be worth its maximum price of

615
00:25:40,420 --> 00:25:43,180
$3, because the strike width is $3.

616
00:25:43,980 --> 00:25:46,000
And again, we have to multiply these figures

617
00:25:46,000 --> 00:25:48,000
by 100 to get their actual values.

618
00:25:48,420 --> 00:25:50,680
So if I short the spread for $106

619
00:25:50,680 --> 00:25:53,860
and it appreciates to a value of $300,

620
00:25:54,420 --> 00:25:57,100
I will lose $194.

621
00:25:57,760 --> 00:26:00,300
But this is just the expiration payoff graph,

622
00:26:00,420 --> 00:26:02,160
and we know that this does not reflect

623
00:26:02,160 --> 00:26:04,360
what will happen before expiration.

624
00:26:04,360 --> 00:26:06,260
So let's go ahead and look at a

625
00:26:06,260 --> 00:26:09,820
performance visualization for this position to see exactly

626
00:26:09,820 --> 00:26:12,860
how the trade performed relative to changes in

627
00:26:12,860 --> 00:26:14,980
the stock price as time was passing.

628
00:26:15,340 --> 00:26:16,980
The first thing to note is the correlation

629
00:26:16,980 --> 00:26:19,400
between the stock price and the spread price,

630
00:26:19,840 --> 00:26:21,740
and since this is a bearish call spread

631
00:26:21,740 --> 00:26:24,080
trade, I want the stock price to fall

632
00:26:24,080 --> 00:26:27,040
and be below $142 at expiration.

633
00:26:27,940 --> 00:26:30,440
About halfway through this trade, with 17 days

634
00:26:30,440 --> 00:26:32,760
to expiration, we can see that the stock

635
00:26:32,760 --> 00:26:37,040
price was approaching the $145 price level, and

636
00:26:37,040 --> 00:26:38,820
we can see that the spread's value was

637
00:26:38,820 --> 00:26:43,080
at $2, representing an unrealized loss of about

638
00:26:43,080 --> 00:26:44,880
$94 at that time.

639
00:26:45,400 --> 00:26:47,500
But as a few more weeks passed, we

640
00:26:47,500 --> 00:26:49,520
can see that the stock price declined steadily,

641
00:26:50,060 --> 00:26:52,440
and with two days to expiration, the stock

642
00:26:52,440 --> 00:26:54,560
price was well below the call spread's strike

643
00:26:54,560 --> 00:26:57,560
prices, and the spread price itself was almost

644
00:26:57,560 --> 00:26:58,100
$0.

645
00:26:58,900 --> 00:27:00,880
So with the best case scenario being that

646
00:27:00,880 --> 00:27:03,580
the spread price falls to $0, it would

647
00:27:03,580 --> 00:27:05,840
make sense at that moment to close that

648
00:27:05,840 --> 00:27:08,680
spread if the price gets close to $0.

649
00:27:09,400 --> 00:27:12,420
Now to close a short call spread, meaning

650
00:27:12,420 --> 00:27:14,640
a call spread that you sold as an

651
00:27:14,640 --> 00:27:16,980
opening trade, you just need to buy back

652
00:27:16,980 --> 00:27:19,360
that same call spread to close it, which

653
00:27:19,360 --> 00:27:21,560
would consist of buying back the short call

654
00:27:21,560 --> 00:27:23,240
and selling the long call.

655
00:27:23,640 --> 00:27:25,600
So in this trade, that would mean buying

656
00:27:25,600 --> 00:27:28,900
back the short $142 call and selling the

657
00:27:28,900 --> 00:27:31,400
long $145 call, and this can be done

658
00:27:31,400 --> 00:27:32,540
in one transaction.

659
00:27:33,200 --> 00:27:35,220
So if I paid $0.20 to buy

660
00:27:35,220 --> 00:27:37,540
back the spread, my net profit would be

661
00:27:37,540 --> 00:27:41,580
$86 because I initially shorted the spread for

662
00:27:41,580 --> 00:27:45,040
$1.06. In terms of this spread's value

663
00:27:45,040 --> 00:27:48,160
at expiration, the stock price was at $142

664
00:27:48,160 --> 00:27:51,880
.26, which means the $142 call had intrinsic

665
00:27:51,880 --> 00:27:55,540
value of $0.26, and the $145 call

666
00:27:55,540 --> 00:27:56,820
expired worthless.

667
00:27:57,700 --> 00:28:00,740
Therefore, the price of the $142-$145

668
00:28:00,740 --> 00:28:03,760
bear call spread at expiration was $0.26,

669
00:28:04,200 --> 00:28:06,780
or a real value of $26.

670
00:28:07,420 --> 00:28:10,040
So if I shorted this spread for $106

671
00:28:10,040 --> 00:28:13,820
and it had value of $26 at expiration,

672
00:28:14,420 --> 00:28:16,080
my profit would be $80.

673
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:18,960
All right, so we've got one vertical spread

674
00:28:18,960 --> 00:28:20,580
strategy left, and then we will get to

675
00:28:20,580 --> 00:28:22,340
the fun stuff, at least in my opinion,

676
00:28:22,740 --> 00:28:24,700
because the next sections are going to be

677
00:28:24,700 --> 00:28:27,720
critical in your understanding of vertical spread profitability

678
00:28:27,720 --> 00:28:29,780
and how you can make more and more

679
00:28:29,780 --> 00:28:31,480
money on your vertical spread positions.

680
00:28:31,840 --> 00:28:34,000
The final of the four vertical spread strategies

681
00:28:34,000 --> 00:28:36,040
that we have to discuss is the bear

682
00:28:36,040 --> 00:28:38,720
put spread, which is sometimes referred to as

683
00:28:38,720 --> 00:28:41,600
simply buying a put spread or a put

684
00:28:41,600 --> 00:28:44,500
debit spread, since you pay to enter the

685
00:28:44,500 --> 00:28:44,860
put spread.

686
00:28:45,240 --> 00:28:47,800
To enter a bear put spread position, a

687
00:28:47,800 --> 00:28:49,560
trader will buy a put spread at one

688
00:28:49,560 --> 00:28:52,600
strike price and short another put option at

689
00:28:52,600 --> 00:28:53,800
a lower strike price.

690
00:28:54,200 --> 00:28:55,620
And the goal is to see the stock

691
00:28:55,620 --> 00:28:58,440
price fall below both of the put spread

692
00:28:58,440 --> 00:29:01,200
strike prices, and that would lead to the

693
00:29:01,200 --> 00:29:02,980
maximum profit at expiration.

694
00:29:03,160 --> 00:29:05,240
And since the put that you purchase will

695
00:29:05,240 --> 00:29:06,820
be more expensive than the put that you

696
00:29:06,820 --> 00:29:09,960
short when you enter the trade, this position

697
00:29:09,960 --> 00:29:11,800
will require that you pay to enter the

698
00:29:11,800 --> 00:29:14,200
position, and for that reason, it is sometimes

699
00:29:14,200 --> 00:29:15,980
called a put debit spread.

700
00:29:16,120 --> 00:29:17,600
So let's take a look at an example

701
00:29:17,600 --> 00:29:19,620
and then move on to the more important

702
00:29:19,620 --> 00:29:20,420
and fun stuff.

703
00:29:20,740 --> 00:29:22,660
At the time of entering this trade, the

704
00:29:22,660 --> 00:29:27,340
stock price was at $780.22. To construct

705
00:29:27,340 --> 00:29:30,120
this bear put spread, we'll buy the 800

706
00:29:30,120 --> 00:29:34,860
put for $44.88 and short the 750

707
00:29:34,860 --> 00:29:39,860
put for $22.63. Both options are in

708
00:29:39,860 --> 00:29:41,840
the 59-day expiration cycle.

709
00:29:42,520 --> 00:29:44,520
The entry price of this spread is therefore

710
00:29:44,520 --> 00:29:48,820
$22.25. So let's go ahead and take

711
00:29:48,820 --> 00:29:51,080
a look at the expiration profit and loss

712
00:29:51,080 --> 00:29:54,100
diagram for this position and then visualize the

713
00:29:54,100 --> 00:29:55,340
trade's actual performance.

714
00:29:55,500 --> 00:29:57,680
The best case scenario is that the stock

715
00:29:57,680 --> 00:30:01,360
price falls below $750 and remains there at

716
00:30:01,360 --> 00:30:04,320
expiration, because in that scenario, the put spread

717
00:30:04,320 --> 00:30:06,220
will be worth the distance between the strike

718
00:30:06,220 --> 00:30:07,800
prices, which is $50.

719
00:30:08,540 --> 00:30:10,440
So if I buy a put spread for

720
00:30:10,440 --> 00:30:15,560
$22.25 and it depreciates to $50, I'll

721
00:30:15,560 --> 00:30:19,620
